<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&message.id=10725#M10725">13</a> of 44
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 974 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV></DIV><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<P>Zamboni wrote:<BR>I think this is a real issue on raids, but trivial in groups. Unless you're doing content WAY over your head (or don't have a tank appropriate for the content), then it's pretty tough for a smart cleric to go oom in xp groups. Yah, CH in groups is a real yawner, but it gets the job done at a fairly minimal cost.<BR><BR>On raids, however, the slow mana regen becomes more of an issue. Clerics have it worse than any other pure caster because our self mana buff doesn't stack with Oak. Chanters have gather, wizzies have familiars and gather, shammies have canni, necros have lich, mages can steal mana from pets and have mod rods (although those are shareable) and druids... well, druids are almost as bad off as clerics, except that they get the little bit extra from their self-buff.<BR><BR>There actually was a gather mana AA for clerics in testing (for DoN, I think), but it never made it off of beta.<BR><BR>The real problem with giving clerics a huge mana regen boost is that it would wreck old content (including relatively recent old content), which is designed around old levels of mana regen. So, what Sony needs to do is figure out a way to increase post-wipe regen without trivializing content.<BR><BR>I'm not a programmer, so I have no clue how tough some of these solutions would be to implement, but here are my suggestions:<BR><BR>To deal with raid mana regen after wipes:<BR><BR>(1) a new raid leader AA that gives a raid 25%/50%/75% of it's mana back. HOWEVER, this ability cannot be activated if anyone in the raid is in an raid level dynamic zone or task.</P>
<P><FONT color=#66cc00>Does thsi mean after a wipe in order to use this ability the raid has to leave the expedition/mission/task before it can be used?&nbsp; So, instead of rezzing and regening normally a raid would get their mana back faster but would have to start the expedition over again, which probably means clearing trash again - wow I think I woudl rez and med.<BR></FONT><BR>(2) a new raid leader AA that basically brings the guildhall hot tub to the raid, for increased hp/mana/end regen.</P>
<P><FONT color=#66cc00>This idea has potential.&nbsp; A triggered raid leader AA that would boost mana regen for a short time.&nbsp; It would have to have a fairly long reuse though.</FONT><BR><BR>(3) an enchanter AA that summons a Ward which increases mana regen (can give the ward 1hp and make it generate insane aggro, if it's too powerful for use during encounters).</P>
<P><FONT color=#66cc00>Again, has potential.</FONT><BR><BR>To deal with cleric mana regen issues in general:<BR><BR>(1) make Armour of the XXX stack with the Oak line (maybe decrease the Armour line hps a bit at the same time).</P>
<P><FONT color=#66cc00>This makes absolutely ZERO sense.&nbsp;&nbsp;Are you&nbsp;looking for a balance issue with&nbsp;other casters?&nbsp; Each caster has his own method of mana regen (chanter&nbsp;- c6 + "leech", wizard - familiar, necro - lich, shaman - canni, mage -&nbsp;mod rod + pet draining, druid - oakskin + MofW, and cleric - AotP) To have two classes' methods stack on ONE class (oakskin + AotP) is just screaming for an uproar from the caster community as unbalanced.&nbsp; Yes c6, oakskin, and mod rods are designed to be cast/used &nbsp;on other characters, but that's the advantage those classes have (you'll notice that, chanters, mages and druids have&nbsp;lesser self only&nbsp;options too).</FONT></P>
<P><FONT color=#66cc00>Clerics have to choose bewteen oakskin+symbol+WoV or conviction+AotP, and unless a shaman is present the latter is always the better option.&nbsp; Add wunshi to the mix and the former is the better choice since AotP and wunshi don't stack (one of our top ten issues).</FONT><BR><BR>(2) increase the FT cap by another 5-10 (for all classes).</P>
<P><FONT color=#66cc00>I'm sure this will happen eventually.&nbsp; I figure every two of three expansions from here on we will see FT cap increasing AAs to compensate for the steadily increasing mana pools.&nbsp; It will probably never be enough but....</FONT><BR><BR>(3) give clerics the mastery of the past AA (even though this wouldn't work on our high level spam heals, at least we'd stop fizzling CH, a level 39 spell that we've cast 100k+ times).</P>
<P><FONT color=#66cc00>I think all casters should have this.</FONT><BR><BR>(4) give clerics a diety-specific familiar with benefits similar to wizzy familiars (I want a giant floating beer stein!)</P>
<P><FONT color=#66cc00>I ask again, are you looking for a caster balance issue?&nbsp; the Wizard familar&nbsp;is a class defining trait.&nbsp; Plus familiars don't make sense from a lore standpoint.</FONT></P>
<P>
<HR>

<P></P></BLOCKQUOTE>Fact is EVERY caster class has this problem.&nbsp; IMO the best solution is to remodel the mana regen rates like the health regen rates - if you sit down and wait, the rate increases steadily.&nbsp; Same goes for endurance.<BR>
