		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Sprite3205 wrote:<BR>
<DIV>Raising the FT cap is about the only thing I'd like to see for additional mana regen.&nbsp; I came back from EQ2 because it was too easy and got boring.&nbsp; I wanted to play the hard game again.&nbsp; It was a huge shock to see the mana regen rate in EQ1 after coming back but I love it because it makes the game harder and that's what I missed.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>It does suck to med and buff after a wipe but I don't think we should be able to turn right around and attempt again.&nbsp; You wipe and pay the price for it.&nbsp; It makes the win that much sweeter and people give that much more effort.&nbsp; Besides, we do have great mana regen for raids, they're called necros.</DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV></DIV>
<P>No one is denying that when you wipe, a group should pay a price, but to go from 0 to 100% mana can take 20 minutes when you take rebuffing into account, and that amount of time is simply too long.&nbsp; Now I do not usually wait that long in group content, but some do.</P>
<P>As for necros on raids: when you have one or two necros and 36 other casters, it's kind of hard to think of necros as a viable mana regen source <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-wink.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0>.&nbsp; Yes, one each of the buffing classes can get regenned faster and be able to rebuff the raid, but that's about it.&nbsp; Along those same lines though on raids you do get the benefit of every mana regen buff available (C6, SA, Steeloak, CoL) and mod rods, where in groups you are lucky to get c6 at times.&nbsp; So, regen on raids is usually faster because more buffs are available.</P>	
		</td></tr>
